# Ollama Model Management

Ollama runs locally on KILO (the Windows workstation) and serves LLMs to OpenClaw via the OpenAI-compatible API. Use this skill to discover models, check their status, and help the user manage them.

## When to use

- User asks "what models do I have?" or "what LLMs are available?"
- User asks to pull, remove, or switch a model
- You need to check if a specific model is loaded in VRAM
- User asks about GPU usage or model performance
- A model request fails and you need to diagnose availability
- User wants to explore or try a new model from the Ollama library

## Ollama API

Ollama is reachable from inside the gateway container at `http://host.docker.internal:11434`.

### List all installed models

```bash
curl -s http://host.docker.internal:11434/api/tags
```

### Check which models are currently loaded in VRAM

```bash
curl -s http://host.docker.internal:11434/api/ps
```

### Get detailed info about a specific model

```bash
curl -s http://host.docker.internal:11434/api/show -d '{"model":"MODEL_NAME"}'
```

### Pull a new model from the Ollama library

```bash
curl -s http://host.docker.internal:11434/api/pull -d '{"name":"MODEL_NAME","stream":false}'
```

Note: Pulling downloads the model to `E:\ollama\models`. Large models (>10GB) may take several minutes. The RTX 5070 Ti has 16GB VRAM, so models up to ~14GB (Q4_K_M quantized) fit fully in VRAM.

### Load a model with a long keepalive (prevent unloading)

```bash
curl -s http://host.docker.internal:11434/api/generate -d '{"model":"MODEL_NAME","prompt":"hi","stream":false,"keep_alive":"24h"}'
```

### Unload a model from VRAM

```bash
curl -s http://host.docker.internal:11434/api/generate -d '{"model":"MODEL_NAME","prompt":"","stream":false,"keep_alive":"0"}'
```

## Hardware constraints

- **GPU**: NVIDIA RTX 5070 Ti 16GB VRAM
- **Model storage**: `E:\ollama\models` (dedicated drive)
- Only one large model can be loaded in VRAM at a time (16GB limit)
- If a model doesn't fit, Ollama will partially offload to CPU (much slower)

## Current Disciplines (registered in OpenClaw)

These models are configured in `openclaw.json` as Zuberi's disciplines:

| Model ID | Discipline | Notes |
|----------|-----------|-------|
| `gpt-oss:20b` | **General expertise (primary)** | 20.9B params, MXFP4, ~13GB. Conversation, reasoning, tool use. 131K context. |
| `qwen2.5-coder:14b` | **Software engineering** | 14.8B params, Q4_K_M, ~9.0GB. Code generation, debugging, refactoring. 131K context. |
| `qwen3-vl:8b` | **Visual analysis** | 8.8B params, Q4_K_M, ~6.1GB. Image input, OCR, diagram interpretation. 131K context. |

## Researching new models

When the user wants to explore new models, use the Ollama library search:

```bash
curl -s "https://ollama.com/search?q=QUERY" | head -100
```

Or use the SearXNG skill to search for model reviews, benchmarks, and comparisons:

```bash
curl -s "http://100.100.101.1:8888/search?q=ollama+MODEL_NAME+benchmark+review&format=json"
```

When recommending models, consider:
- Must fit in 16GB VRAM (prefer Q4_K_M quant under 12GB for full GPU offload)
- Check if a no-think variant is needed (thinking models add 3-6s latency on RTX 5070 Ti)
- Vision models need `"input": ["text", "image"]` in the OpenClaw config
- After pulling a new model, remind the user it needs to be added to `openclaw.json` to be usable by the agent

## Important

- Models are stored on `E:\ollama\models` (not C:\)
- The `OLLAMA_MODELS` env var is set at user level to `E:\ollama\models`
- Always report model sizes and VRAM usage when listing models
- If a model fails to load, check `nvidia-smi` for VRAM availability
- After any model config change, OpenClaw needs a restart: `docker restart openclaw-openclaw-gateway-1`

## Known Issues

- gpt-oss:20b at 95% VRAM causes 30/70 CPU/GPU split — inference becomes much slower when VRAM is nearly full
